led Violet Canal. But when Violet is overrun by killer surges, the Robins must summon all their courage, seamanship, and cunning to save themselves and the scores of others suddenly cast into their care. In this gripping saga, Louisiana native Ken Wells provides a close-up look at the harrowing experiences in the backwaters of New Orleans during and after Katrina. Focusing on the plight of the intrepid Robin family, whose members trace their local roots to before the American Revolution, Wells recounts the landfall of the storm and the tumultuous seventy-two hours afterward, when the Robins' beloved bayou country lay catastrophically flooded and all but forgotten by outside authorities as the world focused its attention on New Orleans. Wells follows his characters for more than two years as they strive, amid mind-boggling wreckage and governmental fecklessness, to rebuild their shattered lives. This is a story about the deep longing for home and a proud bayou people's love of the fertile but imperiled low country that has nourished them.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBayousxLouisianaxSaint Bernard Parish. 0aBayouszLouisianazSaint Bernard Parish. 0aCommunity lifexLouisianaxSaint Bernard Parish. 0aCommunity lifezLouisianazSaint Bernard Parish. 0aDisaster victimsxBiographyxLouisianaxSaint Bernard Parish. 0aDisaster victimszLouisianazSaint Bernard ParishvBiography. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspectsxLouisianaxSaint Bernard Parish. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspectszLouisianazSaint Bernard Parish. 0aWorking classxBiographyxLouisianaxSaint Bernard Parish. 0aWorking classzLouisianazSaint Bernard ParishvBiography. 7aHISTORY / United States / 21st Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is 